<DOC><DOCNO> AP900314-0198 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-90 1557EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f BC-AutoSales 1stLd-Writethru f0140 03-14 0440</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Auto Sales, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0140,0450</SECOND><HEAD>Big Three Sales Dip</HEAD><HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to CORRECT to 6.8 percent sted 2.6 percent decline.Picks up 2nd graf, General Motors ...</NOTE><BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE><BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Early March sales of cars and light trucks madeby the nation's Big Three automakers dipped 6.8 percent comparedwith slow sales a year ago, the companies said Wednesday.   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. saidthey sold cars and light trucks at an average daily rate of 27,289during the March 1-10 period this year, compared with 29,281 duringthe same time last year.   Car sales fell 7.7 percent, and truck sales were down 5.4percent.   March and April usually usher in a more bouyant car and truckbuying season as Americans shake off the winter and take to thehighways.   But incentives offered during January and February of last yearhad attracted would-be March and April buyers, depressing the salesrate for the latter two months.   The March 1989 sales rate was the lowest during the first ninemonths of the year. Sales hit the skids during the final threemonths of last year, but the pace picked up slightly after thefirst of the year.   Despite comparison with a slow sales period a year ago, earlyMarch sales were lower this year.   Through March 10 of this year, the car and truck selling ratewas running 2.6 percent behind last year's rate. Car sales were off5.6 percent but truck sales were up 2.2 percent, mainly because ofstrong Chrysler minivan sales in January.   Chrysler said its early March car and truck sales were running11.3 percent behind last year's pace, with car sales down 9.1percent and truck sales off 13.4 percent.   But for the year, Chrysler's car and truck sales were running0.2 percent ahead of last year, with car sales down 6.9 percent andtruck sales up 6.8 percent.   Ford said its early March car sales were down 8.1 percent andtruck sales were down 3.1 percent, combining for a 6.1 percentsales decrease from year-ago levels. For the year, Ford's vehiclesales were running 6.5 percent behind last year, with car salesdown 8.6 percent and truck sales down 3.5 percent.   GM's combined car and truck sales for early March was down 5.7percent compared with last year, as car sales fell 7.1 percent andtruck sales dropped 3.1 percent. So far this year, GM's car saleswere down 3.2 percent and truck sales were up 4.7 percent,combining for a sales rate 0.7 percent below last year.</TEXT></DOC>